        longDescBeijing: "<p>Beijing, the capital of the People's Republic of China, is a city of immense history and cultural significance. It has been the center of power for much of the country's history, which is evident in its grand architecture.</p><p>Explore the vast complex of the Forbidden City, the former imperial palace, walk along the historic Great Wall, and visit the serene Temple of Heaven. Modern Beijing is also a hub of art, cuisine, and commerce, offering a dynamic blend of old and new.</p>",
        longDescShanghai: "<p>Shanghai, a global financial hub, is a city of superlatives. Its futuristic skyline, dominated by the Shanghai Tower and the Oriental Pearl TV Tower, is a sight to behold.</p><p>Stroll along the Bund to admire the colonial-era architecture, explore the trendy boutiques and art galleries in the French Concession, or find tranquility in the classical Yu Garden. Shanghai is a testament to China's rapid development and a must-visit for any traveler.</p>",
        longDescXian: "<p>Xi'an is one of the oldest cities in China and the eastern terminus of the Silk Road. Its most famous attraction is the Terracotta Army, a vast collection of life-sized terracotta sculptures depicting the armies of Qin Shi Huang, the first Emperor of China.</p><p>The city itself is surrounded by a well-preserved ancient city wall, which you can cycle on for incredible views. Don't miss the Muslim Quarter for a vibrant culinary experience.</p>",
        longDescGuilin: "<p>Guilin's landscape is the stuff of classic Chinese paintings. Located in Southern China, it is world-renowned for its otherworldly karst topography.</p><p>The best way to experience its beauty is by taking a cruise down the Li River, where you'll see limestone peaks, bamboo groves, and tranquil villages. You can also explore the Reed Flute Cave, a natural limestone cave with impressive stalactites and stalagmites illuminated by colorful lights.</p>",
        longDescZhangjiajie: "\u003cp\u003eZhangjiajie is famous for its towering pillar-like sandstone formations set within a UNESCO-listed national park – an otherworldly landscape perfect for hiking and photography.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eHighlights\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eZhangjiajie National Forest Park\u003c/strong\u003e – home to the famous quartz-sandstone pillars.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAvatar Hallelujah Mountains\u003c/strong\u003e – scenic viewpoints inspired cinematic landscapes.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGlass Bridge (Zhangjiajie Grand Canyon)\u003c/strong\u003e – a thrilling suspended walkway with dramatic views.\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e",
        longDescJiuzhaigou: "\u003cp\u003eJiuzhaigou is renowned for its vivid turquoise lakes, multi-tiered waterfalls and pristine alpine valleys – a scenic gem in Sichuan province.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eHighlights\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRize Valley\u003c/strong\u003e – colorful lakes and clear water reflections.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShuzheng Valley\u003c/strong\u003e – classic views of layered waterfalls.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHiking & Photography\u003c/strong\u003e – boardwalk trails provide easy access to viewpoints.\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e",
        longDescYangtze: "\u003cp\u003eThe Yangtze is China's longest river, famous for the dramatic Three Gorges and popular river cruises that combine scenery with cultural visits.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eHighlights\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThree Gorges\u003c/strong\u003e – steep-sided gorges carved by the river offering spectacular views.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYangtze Cruises\u003c/strong\u003e – multi-day cruise options between Chongqing and Yichang.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCultural stops\u003c/strong\u003e – riverside towns, temples and local markets.\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e",
        longDescIching: "\u003cp\u003eThe \u003cstrong\u003eI Ching\u003c/strong\u003e (also written \u003cem\u003eiching\u003c/em\u003e, Chinese: \u003cstrong\u003e易经\u003c/strong\u003e) – literally the \u003cem\u003eBook of Changes\u003c/em\u003e – is one of the oldest Chinese classics. It combines cosmology, philosophy and a system of 64 hexagrams used historically for divination and decision-making.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eHistory & structure\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe iching developed over millennia. Each of its 64 hexagrams is formed from six lines (broken or unbroken). Traditional commentaries – the Ten Wings – expanded the text into a rich philosophical work used by scholars and sages.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eHow iching divination works\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cp\u003eModern iching methods use coins or yarrow stalk techniques to generate a hexagram. Interpreting the iching hexagram involves reading its meaning, line transformations, and how it relates to your question.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eWhy read the I Ching today?\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePhilosophical insight:\u003c/strong\u003e iching offers frameworks for change and decision-making.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCultural context:\u003c/strong\u003e Understanding 易经 deepens appreciation for Chinese thought, history and literature.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePractical uses:\u003c/strong\u003e meditation, creative prompts, and reflective decision processes.\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003ch3\u003eFurther reading & resources\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cp\u003eRecommended translations and commentaries include works by Richard Wilhelm (translated by Cary F. Baynes), and modern commentaries that explain iching hexagrams in contemporary terms.\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch3\u003eLearn more\u003c/h3\u003e\u003cp\u003eIf you are visiting China and interested in cultural tours, ask local museums or cultural centers about lectures and exhibits related to the \u003cem\u003eiching\u003c/em\u003e and classical Chinese philosophy.\u003c/p\u003e",
